# CS 255 Portfolio Submission

This repository includes my CS 255 portfolio artifacts. From Project One, I included my Business Requirements Document. 
From Project Two, I included my System Design Document. 
These projects show my work with gathering requirements, analyzing a client’s needs, and designing a system based on those needs.

## Reflection

The DriverPass project was for a client who wanted a system to help students prepare for driving tests. 
  DriverPass needed an online system where customers could create accounts, choose training packages, schedule driving lessons, take practice tests, and view their progress. 
The system also needed employee tools for scheduling, reports, user accounts, and DMV updates.


I think I did well turning the interview details into clear requirements and diagrams. 
The client gave a lot of information, so I had to organize it into functional requirements, nonfunctional requirements, users, and system features. 
I also think my activity diagrams helped show how important processes, like scheduling a driving lesson, would work.


If I could revise one part, I would improve the diagrams even more by making them cleaner and easier to read. 
Some diagrams can get crowded when there are too many users, actions, or system parts. 
In the future, I would spend more time simplifying the layout so the design is easier for both technical and nontechnical people to understand.


I interpreted the user’s needs by looking at what DriverPass actually wanted the system to do. 
For example, Liam wanted customers to schedule lessons online, download reports, track activity, and receive DMV updates. 
I used those needs to shape the use case, activity, sequence, and class diagrams. 
Considering user needs is important because a system can be technically correct but still fail if it does not solve the client’s real problems.


My approach to designing software is to start with the requirements, identify the users, break the system into main features, 
and then model how those features should work. In the future, I would continue using interviews, requirement lists, use case diagrams, activity diagrams, and class diagrams to analyze and design systems before coding starts.
